Exercise 1: Exploratory Data Analysis

  1. Visualize the distribution of score in the dataframe evals.
evals %>%
  summarise(mean(score))
##   mean(score)
## 1     4.17473
evals %>%
  summarise(median(score))
##   median(score)
## 1           4.3
ggplot(data = evals, mapping = aes(x = score)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30) + 
  labs(x = "Score", y = "Frequency" )

The mean score being 4.17 means that the students rated the courses/professors really highly. The median score is 4.3. The data is also skewed towards the right, or positively skewed. I would not have expected the data to be positively skewed because I would have expected the scores to be more varied, so more random.

  1. Visualize and describe the relationship between score and bty_avg using geom_point() to represent the data.
ggplot(data = evals, mapping = aes(x = bty_avg, y = score)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Relationship between 'Average beauty rating of professors' and 'Score'", x = "Average Beauty Rating", y = "Score")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = evals, mapping = aes(x = bty_avg, y = score)) + 
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Relationship between 'Average beauty rating of professors' and 'Score'", x = "Average Beauty Rating", y = "Score")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The scatter plot shows that there is no correlation between scores and the average beauty rating. The jitter randomises the data even more, there are more clusters in the data than in the scatter plot so it shows the variation in the data.

Exercise 2: Simple Linear regression with a numerical predictor

  1. Fit a linear model called score_bty_fit to predict average professor evaluation score from average beauty rating (bty_avg). Print the regression output using tidy().
score_bty_fit <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm") %>%
  fit(score ~ bty_avg, data = evals) 
tidy(score_bty_fit) 

ggplot(data = score_bty_fit)
